      "description": "Steady-state staircase from 10% to 100% throttle. Each step dwells long enough to settle, and the tail of each is used to compute thrust, electrical power and efficiency (g/W) plus loop time / CPU load at that operating point. This is the primary efficiency + performance baseline.\nHold time is 10s (up from an initial 6s): the ARK 4IN1 + JS Technology 2306 1800KV + HQProp 5136 bench shows real mechanical vibration/resonance across most of the RPM range - thrust coefficient of variation up to 66% sample-to -sample at some points (e.g. ~20k RPM / 60% throttle) even though RPM and current are rock-stable. A 3s tail (300 samples) wasn't enough for the mean to converge repeatably (up to 20% swing between back-to-back captures on unchanged hardware); a 5s tail approximately doubles the samples averaged. This does not fix the underlying vibration - likely prop balance, a loose mount, or a structural resonance - only makes the baseline less sensitive to it. See Thresholds.efficiency_drop_pct in hwci/baseline.py for the matching percentage-tolerance widening.\n",
